    <title>SpaceX’s Polaris Dawn completed the first private spacewalk</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/u0p-4-SQbkWbu_nWzoFceRf6umM=/214x0:1942x1152/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73580951/spacex_polaris_dawn_spacewalk.0.png" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;&lt;em&gt;Privatey-trained astronaut Jared Isaacman emerges from the capsule.&lt;/em&gt; | Screenshot: SpaceX&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="o8eguh"&gt;SpaceX’s Polaris Dawn astronauts &lt;a href="https://x.com/SpaceX/status/1834154037606056327"&gt;successfully performed a spacewalk&lt;/a&gt;, marking the first done by a private company. After depressurizing SpaceX’s Dragon capsule, the billionaire funding the mission, Jared Isaacman, emerged from the spacecraft early Thursday morning.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="VskEMJ"&gt;With his torso and head fully sticking outside the capsule, Isaacman performed tests on SpaceX’s new spacesuits, which are designed for increased mobility. “Back at home, we all have a lot of work to do,” Isaacman said during the spacewalk. “But from here, it sure looks like a perfect world.”&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div id="FCG8Xw"&gt;
